column3: Defect Description
column4: Error-Prone Scenario Analysis

column3: String should be printed in reverse order. String is parsed character by character in reverse order while string[i] character is printed. Conditional is initialized as (i=string.length() - 1, i $<$ string.length(), i--)
column4: When parsing arrays or strings as arrays, the most common way is to parse from the start of the string or array to the end with the for loop conditional (i=0, i<string.length(), i++). When reverse parsing, i must be set to the length of the string or array – 1, with the conditional that i $>$= 0, and with i decrementing by 1.

column3: Initially adopted a push model to run tests real time at the time the event was received. After increasing test volume, scheduling caused hotspots and oversaturation of test agent system resources resulting in test failures. Refactored to use of local queueing with N test worker services to evenly space testing and avoid overloading test agents.
column4: The push model led to uneven resource consumption, with bursts of tests overwhelming test agents. As test volume increased, resource contention caused failures. The root cause was the lack of a controlled scheduling mechanism to distribute tests more evenly. The issue was resolved by implementing local queueing with worker services to regulate test execution.

column3: While parsing through a string, each character should be checked to see if it matches a given character and if it is the given nth instance of that character in the string. If it is the correct instance of the correct character, the character ‘0’ should be printed, otherwise the original character should be printed. In the case where the character did not match and the case where the character matched the given character and instance the behavior was correct. The case where the character matched but the instance did not match was neglected.
column4: When reviewing the design of one’s own work, N conditions = 3 : character and instance matches, character matches and instance does not match, and character does not match. The conditions reviewed were the first and third scenario: n=2 $<$ N=3 conditions were reviewed.

column3: C language, using strncpy() the length of the string being copied was one less than intended when trying to perform a substring operation with the function.
column4: Off by one type of error. Just assumed that the length being specified as the end index minus the start index would be correct when it was just one off.

column3: When grading a programming assignment, I wrote a shell script to display everyone's write-up file one after another in the terminal. However, some students put their write-up in a sub directory, and thus the script would not work in this case.
column4: This is an example of Biased review because I did not take into account the possible case of the write-up file not being located in the repo's root directory.

column3: In game players choose an acting role to perform. They must stay on the role until they complete it. My program did not track a players role properly, allowing for a player to take multiple roles
column4: I was focused on making sure a player could take a role and did not make sure they were prevented from taking additional roles. Fixed the error by including a check to make sure player can only have 1 role

column3: EC2 test agents (t4g.nano) began failing to report testing result metrics due to overloaded CPU and memory utilization resulting in inability to complete tests within the designated timeframe. Upgrade to larger instance size necessary to restore operation.
column4: The selected EC2 instance type (t4g.nano) did not have sufficient resources to handle the workload, leading to performance degradation and failed test executions. This issue was likely caused by underestimating resource requirements or not performing adequate load testing before deployment.

column3: When comparing Integers in Java, == was used instead of .equals, resulting in a false boolean value even when the numeric values of the Integers was the same.
column4: I didn’t know that Java uses caching for Integer values between -128 and 127 and creates new references for Integers outside of that range. So comparing Integers withing that range with == will reference the same value and return true but using == between to equally numeric Integers outside that range will return false.

column3: Was trying to edit a variable that I never initialized
column4: In this case, after working on a class for a larger program I stopped for the night. When I came back, I tried accessing the new class to use it to further my program. However, I forgot to initialize it in main, so when testing it didn’t work.

column3: In C. Checked for the pattern “/*” rather than “$\backslash$*” in a char * (string) as the design document specifies
column4: I think because / is more of a common character for me to hit than \, and since they are so similar, I misinterpreted the requirement and implemented it wrong

column3: I mistakenly called `fetchDeviceInfo()` instead of `fetchDeviceDetails()`, leading to incomplete metadata retrieval in my Smart Home Privacy Assistant.
column4: The function names were too similar, making them easy to confuse. Since both returned valid but different results, I did not notice the mistake immediately.

column3: I copied the following line: let prev_under_ar c_index = under_arc.prev _arc_index; into: let next_under_ar c_index = under_arc.prev _arc_index; but it should have been: let next_under_ar c_index = under_arc.next _arc_index;
column4: This is a post-completio n error because I named the variable correctly (thus allowing it to be accessed and allowing the program to compile) but I did not change what the variable was assigned to allowing the program to compile. This bug took me a while to find.

column3: In C. Initialized a char * (pointer to a char variable) as just a char (just a char variable). After deciding to make a pointer rather than an array and deleting the array [], I forgot to add the * to make it a pointer rather than just a character itself
column4: Did not notice I forgot to enter in a * until after I had written several more lines of code and the next compile failed. I already finished taking out the [] marking the variable type as an array, and I think my mind considered this as the main subtask, forgetting I also must add the * to the end of the variable type to properly change the type from an array to a pointer.

column3:
In Java, using the system line separator leads to undefined behavior dependent on the system since the line separator is represented by “
” on Windows and “
” on UNIX systems. This is in the documentation. Parsing such code based on line separators can be undefined in certain settings such as with files containing new line characters “
”.
column4: Assumed that the behavior in which the system line separator which worked on Windows would extend to other development environments as well when later investigation into the documentation revealed otherwise.

column3: Overlooked addition of required IAM permissions when deploying new Bedrock testing to test agents using AWS CDK.
column4: The required IAM permissions were not included in the AWS CDK deployment, leading to permission failures on the EC2 test agents when interacting with the Bedrock API. This issue arose due failing to verify IAM policies before deployment.

column3: When performing a left AVL rotation on node X, node X must be established as node Y’s left child and node Y must replace node X as node X’s parent’s child. When performing the rotation node Y’s parent was set as node X’s parent, but node X’s parent’s child was not replaced.
column4: When working with nodes X and Y, the most salient references that must be updated are references stemming from nodes X and Y. Therefore node X’s parent is correctly set to node Y, node Y’s left child is set to node X, and node Y’s parent is set to node X’s parent, but node Y’s child is not updated.

column3: While parsing an integer array nums, true should be returned if there are any duplicates. A duplicate boolean was set to the value of the current int of the array and checked if it existed in a hashmap of all previous ints of the array. Instead of returning when the condition became true, each value of the array was parsed before the true condition of the last value of the array was returned.
column4: The logic of setting a boolean to the value of the check between the current int and all previous ints was correct, the step of returning early when that boolean was true was forgotten.

column3: When initially coding the structure for the Magic Trees A1 assignment, the number of -'s (later changed to spaces) was based on a variable which was set to the current line number to the power of 2. The tree grows exponentially from the bottom, which is the last part printed, so the variable should be based on the(total lines - the current line number) to the power of 2.
column4: When working with iterative indexes, typically we start from 0 or 1 and iterative positively. When working with printing an tree from the end to the starts, the overall order must be reversed too.

column3: In the Magic Trees assignment, I had a yCount variable meant to count the number of ‘Y’s printed in the last line containing Y’s. The variable ended up equaling the actual Y count / 2, and logic was built around it to account for that, but future logic tried to use the variable as if it was accurately set to the actual Y count.
column4: The variable yCount did not actually accurately count Y’s, but gave the impression of doing so due to the variable name. This could also correlate with a mode similar to ‘Omissions following interruptions’ and ‘Forgetting something has been done’ as something like ‘Misinterpreting something that has been done’.

column3: In the Magic Trees assignment, when printing the number of spaces, depending on the line, the total spaces would be correct or too many, depending on the pattern needed in the current line.
column4: The number of spaces needed per line depended on the line number and its reverse log 2 base. The reverse exponential factor along with variations in patters of spaces, slashes (\, /) and Y’s led to inconsistent applications of overarching logic when printing.

column3: Student replaced value 0x7FFFFFFF representing 0 in the sign bit followed by all 1’s in binary with value 0xFFFFFFFF representing all 1’s in binary.
column4: The two values used have a very similar appearance of 7 F’s and both contain 31 1’s in the non-sign bits in binary. Student temporarily deleted the value to test something and replaced the original 0x7FFFFFFF value with 0xFFFFFFFF.

column4: I mistook how arrays are handled in C vs how pointers are handled in C, as pointers are a newer concept to me, and this is only my second class coding in C.

column3: The grading script required the filename `Q1_percent.py` to run `pytest`. However, student submissions included additional identifiers in filenames, such as `studentname_4480817_129425548_Q1_percent.py`. Since the script expected an exact filename match, `pytest` threw a "File Not Found" error.
column4: The script was designed to work with a predefined filename but failed due to filename variations. There was no mechanism to automatically identify or rename files before running `pytest`, leading to failing tests.

column3: Initially for cost reasons, some EC2 test agents were IPv6 only. Later I updated all test agents to dual stack. However, automated unit testing in CI/CD pipeline included a validation of IPv6 only EC2 instances which no longer existed resulting in a build failure.
column4: The CI/CD pipeline continued to check for IPv6-only instances even after all test agents were converted to dual stack. The test logic was not updated to reflect the infrastructure change, leading to failures in automated validation.

column3: AWS Lambda functions intermittently failed to utilize new code following UpdateFunctionCode operation. After failed attempts with adding sleep intervals, discovered that Lambda code updates adhere to an eventually consistent update model, wherein new code is not guaranteed to be accessible immediately after an update. Refactored to leverage an API providing the update status.
column4: The assumption that updated Lambda code would be immediately available led to failures when old versions continued executing. The initial workaround of inserting sleep intervals did not reliably resolve the issue. The root cause was eventually identified as AWS’s eventual consistency model for Lambda deployments, necessitating the use of an API to check update status before invoking the function.
column5: Lack of Knowledge, Difficulties with exponential developments

column3: EBS block volumes intermittently fail to fully attach to EC2 instances resulting in stuck volumes, failed tests, and occupied /dev/xvdN device alias (do not appear in OS while AWS control plane believes they are in use). Added more robust error handling (force detach and block device alias from future testing).
column4: The AWS control plane reported the volume as attached, but the OS did not recognize it, leading to failed tests and resource conflicts. This issue stems from inconsistencies between AWS’s internal state tracking and actual EC2 instance state. The problem was mitigated by implementing force-detach logic and preventing reuse of affected block device aliases in subsequent tests.

column3: While waiting for AWS EFS volumes to transition to available status, excessive API polling requests resulted in 529 throttling errors (request limits are not well documented). Introduced sleep spacing between requests to work around.
column4: The script repeatedly polled the AWS API without rate limiting, leading to excessive requests and API throttling (529 errors). AWS does not clearly document the request limits for this operation, leading to unexpected failures. The issue was resolved by introducing a delay between requests.
column5: Lack of Knowledge, Difficulties with exponential developments

column3: BigQuery SQL queries intermittently failed due to invalid characters in large multiline stdout / stderr output captured and stored during test execution that failed to escape properly in bash test scripts. Used base64 encoding and decoding to resolve.
column4: The test script failed to properly escape or sanitize special characters when capturing and storing stdout/stderr output. This led to malformed SQL queries when inserting the output into BigQuery, causing intermittent failures. The issue was resolved by encoding the output in base64 before storage and decoding it when needed.

column3: RabbitMQ messages lost during high volume queueing operations. Issue due to lack of ConfirmSelect and WaitForConfirm acknowledgements when using HTTP API with curl
column4: System failed to ensure message durability due to reliance on an (incorrect) assumption that messages sent via HTTP API would be durably queued. The absence of ConfirmSelect and WaitForConfirm led to silent message loss under high load conditions.

column3: I was trying to transcribe the expression 1 / (2 * (f_x - y_d)) into code but instead I wrote 1 / 2 * (f_x - y_d) which caused issued with evaluation order and caused to expression to be slightly off.
column4: This is a rule encoding deficiency because I failed to apply the correct parenthesis to get the expression order right. I understand the rules around expression order and parenthesis but did not apply them correctly in this case.

column3: This was a while ago. I wrote some buggy code to remove all items from a list that satisfied some condition: for (int i = 0; i < list.length(); i++) { var item = list[i] if (item should be removed) { list.removeAt(i) } } This code doesn't work correctly because as you remove items, that reduces the length of the list. But the iterator variable item i still increments. This leads to items which appear right after a removed item to be skipped. Consider the following variant of this error:
column4: This is an example of applying a strong but now wrong rule. Using a for loop to iterate through a list like this is common practice and is usually an effective solution for doing something to each element of a list. This technique is the strong rule. However, in this case it is incorrect because the list changes and becomes smaller as you iterate through it. In this case, it requires the programmer to give additional thought to the situation beyond traditional utilization of a for loop list iterator.

column3: I utilized the Rust standard library's priority queue implementation as part of an algorithm implementation I was working on. At first, I assumed it was a min-heap priority queue. I assumed this for two reasons: 1. Most priority queue libraries that I have used in the past implement min-heap. 2. It made my task easier for it to be a min-heap. In actuality, it was a max-heap, causing a defect in my code that had to be addressed.
column4: This is an example of applying "strong-but-no w-wrong" rule because in the past I have utilized min-heap libraries which formed a rule that priority queues are usually min-heap. In the case of the Rust standard library however this rule turned out to be incorrect.

column3: This defect occurred a long time ago when I was first learning Java. I did not know about the Java ArrayList class but wanted to add new items to the end of an array. So, I wrote code that created a new array that was n+1 size, copied over the existing array, and added the new item to the new empty spot at the end. In practice, this is significantly inefficient when compared to ArrayList because ArrayList doubles in capacity whenever it runs out of empty spaces. This gives it a amortized runtime of O(1) compared to my naive approach which has a best-case runtime of O(n).
column4: This is an example of lack of knowledge because I was unaware of the use ArrayList class built-in to Java which did exactly what I wanted in a way that is significantly more efficient then my approach. (See fig. 2)

column3: Last quarter I helped develop a Chrome extension as part of a class project that removed ads, videos, and other extraneous elements from web pages. One of the sites we tested would very occasionally throw up a pop-up, and if it did this while our extension was running it would completely break the site because the button to close the pop-up would get deleted by our extension. In this case, the user would have to reload the site. We did not have time to investigate and fix this bug.
column4: I'm not sure what kind of error mode this is. My best guess is Biased review because this is a situation we did not account for and did not expect, but it could also be lack of knowledge because I did not know how to fix this. That being said I probably could've found a way given more time, but I wanted to avoid creating website-specifi c workarounds for situations like this because it would have greatly expanded the scope of the project.

column3: This was a defect I actually shipped in an earlier version of my bitscalc.com site. Basically, I spent a lot of time styling my website to give it a unique and compelling look. However, I only tested my site using the Firefox web browser on dark mode. There were multiple visual defects when using Chrome or light mode in the earlier version of my site. It took me a long time to become aware of this (only after sending the site to an associate) and even longer before I actually fixed this issue. This defect is especially interesting to me because it was part of a product I actually released and had to fix after the fact.
column4: This is an example of Biased review. I did not even think to check to make sure the style worked on other browsers or when light mode was enabled. I just assumed that if it looked good on Firefox dark mode it would look good on other platforms and configurations, which turned out not to be the case.

column3: Last week I was grading student code submissions and as part of that process I had to type the following command many times: cd ../a2-{student repo name} This week I was grading another assignment and I had to type a slightly different command: cd ../toyos-{studen t repo name} However, I very often typed the first command.
column4: I believe this is strong-but-now wrong rule because the typing the first command many times formed a strong rule in my thinking that was incorrect now that I was grading a similar but different assignment. My only confusion here is that to me this feels like it could be happening at a skill-based performance level because I was not really concentrating on the task as I was doing it. In other words, typing this command felt automatic to me. In that case it might satisfy the mode of double capture slip.

column3: When grading some student's coding assignments, I frequently encountered several submissions that would not compile or would fail before running the tests. I first assumed these submissions were defective, but it turned out to be something else. Students were supposed to mark their submission commit as a3-submit, and my grading script automatically checked out this submit. However, not all students labeled their commit correctly. This turned out to be the case regarding the submissions that were failing. It took me a while to realize this, and I had to go back and re-grade those submissions with the correct commit checked out.
column4: This is an example of Biased review because I did not account for students who did not label their submission commit correctly. I was aware of the possibility not all students would name their commit correctly, but I was unaware of how it would cause problems for my grading. I did not think to account for all cases in this situation.

column3: Entered step instead of stepi
column4: During my “bomb” assignment for CSCI 247, I had to be careful not to blow up my bomb by going too far in the instructions while using the debugger. To do this, I used the command “stepi,” which allowed me to go forward one step in assembly. This should not be confused with “step”, which goes forward one C instruction, which is a lot further than I wanted to test. Unfortunately, since they look similar, I experienced Perceptual confusions and entered step as a command, which ended up blowing up my bomb.

column3: Used space in terminal which enters last command out of habit, crashing my program
column4: During that same bomb assignment, I figured out that when simply pressing enter the previous command is used, which is quite efficient when doing the same step over and over again. After using this a lot, I went back to pen and paper, devising a strategy before trying again. When trying again, I entered “continue” in gdb to go to my breakpoint, and although I should have typed “stepi” to go to the next step and then continued to use it via the enter key, I immediately pressed enter out of habit, intending to go forward one step but instead using continue which, since I had not more breakpoints set, blew up the bomb. This is an example of strong-but-now-wrong: I was so used to enter going forward one line of code that I expected it to do the same even when the previous command was not stepi.

column3: Did not fully follow all cases when reimplementing a function in a bugged program
column4: While fixing a bug in a program given to me in a lab, I noticed an incorrect usage of unsigned integers which created overflows. To fix this, I deleted the entire implementation, creating a while loop which would prevent overflow. However, I failed to realize that the initial for loop I deleted on its first cycle would print differently than on the other cycles, and this caused my program to give unexpected results, failing the tests. I believe this to be an example of a post-completion error, since I first needed to fix the overflow (step A), and then reimplement the special case handling on the first iteration (step B), and since step B is not necessary to completing step A and immediately follows it, I forgot to do it.

column3: Error while working with hexadecimal values
column4: While working on an assignment using hexadecimal values, I was meant to choose the max value. While working this out in my head, I first chose by the tens digits, and then when I saw a 9 in the one's digit I assumed that the number would be the greatest, regardless of what any of the other numbers had in the one's digit, since this would be the case if I were working in standard decimal format. This was me committing a strong-but-now-wrong error since in hexadecimal 9 is not the greatest value, F is. It turns out, there was a value with an A in the ones digit, which is greater than 9 meaning I was incorrect, and this caused me quite a bit of confusion when my code disagreed with me.

column3: Printed “-” rather than spaces in Magic Trees problem
column4: In the magic trees problem assigned to us in class, I did not replace the “-” characters with spaces, as required in the specification. This is a post-completion error, as the instruction to replace those characters was the last line in the spec, and was not a necessary condition to complete the task before it, which was more important to the actual functionality of the program. Most likely, my brain got tired of reading and I skipped to looking at the example diagrams, not realizing I was missing a step.

column3: Did not sort correctly in LeetCode problem
column4: While solving a LeetCode problem where I was asked to sort items by the frequency of said items. Then, the instructions said that if multiple values had the same frequency, that I should sort them by decreasing order. However, since this was the last step, and was not necessary to the task before, I forgot to do so, committing a post-completion error, and was surprised when my result was not accepted.

column3: Used undefined data type in C
column4: While coding in C, I used the data type “bool,” and was surprised when I got an error message that the type “bool” was undefined. After looking it up, I found out that earlier version of C did not have that data type, and that I could either use an integer or define it at the top of the file. This error happened because I was told that booleans are in C and use the name bool, and therefore updated my C schema, not realizing that this was only true for certain versions of C, and that this was not true in the version I was using. This leads me to believe the cause of my error was a rule-encoding deficiency.

column3: Forgot to compile file after making changes
column4: While working on an assignment, I had to frequently make updates to a file, which would thereafter have to be compiled. At one point, after making a change, I forgot to compile, which meant I was not seeing my changes incorporated, which took me a minute to understand while debugging. This is an example of a post-completion error, as it was the last step in the sequence required to edit the file, and it was not required to complete the main task of editing the file, which is what my brain was focused on, taking up the majority of my attention.

column3: Personal project briefly broke due to issues with HTML tags
column4: A user of one of my personal projects notified me that it was no longer working. Upon closer inspection, I discovered it had broken across all platforms. The issue was rooted in how I was identifying elements to edit on webpages: I grabbed them by their HTML tags, hoping that they would not be changed during updates to the website. But evidently they did, and it is an example of an error causing a fault that did not immediately lead to a failure. The error itself is in my opinion an example of a lack of knowledge: I did not know how permanent the HTML tags were, and if they would be changed or not by updates, as I have no knowledge of the eternal workings of the websites I am creating extensions for in my personal project.

column3: Distracted by working on too many separate functions
column4: While doing a class assignment in a brand new topic, I started trying multiple things to test out the functionality of what I was learning (buffer overflow attacks). When I came back I started toflesh out one of these things and was surprised when I was getting unexpected outputs. I eventually realized that my unfinished framework from earlier was breaking things down the line, as it was never meant to be finalized. This is an example of an omission following an interruption: the time I took away from the computer caused me to forget that there were other aspects of the attack that were unfinished, and so I omitted the lines that would have caused the program to run correctly.

column3: The first example is an error I made on an assignment where I was to compare a list of runtimes and sort them in order from least (fastest) to greatest (slowest). The submission was to be a pdf constructed using LaTex. I mistakenly used greater than or equal to symbol ( ? ) instead of the correct greater than symbol ( < ).
column4: I believe this occurred during the coding and review stage because I used the wrong symbol when writing the LaTex code and failed to recognize my mistake when reviewing my answers in the pdf output and at the skill-based performance level. I am highly confident that this error was the result of Perceptual confusions. ? looks very similar to < so used it instead.

column3: The second example is an error I made on an assignment where I was to create a function that takes in an array of items in a set and an array of relations in a set and determines if the set is transitive. Return true if it is false if it’s not. The assignment description gave a few examples of correct and incorrect inputs but didn’t show any examples of edge cases. I forgot to include the null set edge case leading to the function returning false instead of true.
column4: I believe this occurred during the coding stage and at the knowledge-based performance level. I am highly confident that this error was the result of Bias Review. The instructions only contained examples of true and false sets so I focused on getting those to work. Once they returned the proper values for all of the sets I assumed I had successfully covered all the cases which led to me skipping over the null set edge case.

column3: Another example is I was working on a homework assignment with multiple problems. The instructions stated to solve the following problem, how we were to format our answers, when the assignments was due, and at the end to write on the top of our paper if we worked alone or with a team. I forgot to put that I worked alone on the top and as a result lost a significant amount of points on the assignment.
column4: I believe this occurred at the requirement level as I skipped a requirement and at the review level as I was focused on reviewing the answers to thequestions. I am highly confident this is a Post-Completion Error. Writing if I worked alone was the last step and it was smaller and nonessential to the main task of completing the homework.

column3: Another error I personally made is on a quiz the question was “to write down a recurrence that computes a^n using divide and conquer. For example, if we are trying to compute 28, our algorithm should first compute b=24 and then return b*b. Be sure to include cases for both odd and even n.” I incremented n by -2 each recursion instead of n/2.
column4: I believe this occurred at the coding stage as it was when I was actually writing the code that this occurred. This quiz was timed so I did not have time to review my code. I have a medium level of confidence this occurred at the knowledge-based level and is a Selectivity error. I missed the logically important information that I was supposed to use divide and conquer because I was focused on including both odd and even cases.

column3: The final error I personally made that I can remember for purposes of this project occurred when I was trying to give a runtime analysis of a program similar to binary search. I recognized it was similar to binary search and assumed the runtime was O(n log n), the runtimeof binary search. I focused on proving the runtime was O(n log n) instead of computing it from scratch which resulted in me getting the wrong runtime.
column4: I believe this occurred at the design stage as I assumed the solution instead of working to find the best solution. I am highly confident that this occurred at the knowledge-based level and is Confirmation bias. I was trying to confirm the solution and only focusing on the psychologically stagnant information that supported that instead of the logically important information I needed to calculate the correct runtime.

column3: The first example is from a Student who was modifying a Radix sort algorithm to sort negative numbers as well as positive numbers. The student updated all functions in Radix sort but it still wasn’t working correctly. This was because they had forgotten to add a way to separate the negative numbers from the positive numbers so the array of negative numbers was empty and all values were in the positive numbers array.
column4: This occurred at the coding stage and I believe at the skill-based level. I am highly confident this is a Post-Completion Error as it was the smaller final step in the larger task of updating the Radix sort algorithm.

column3: The second example is from a Student who was working on the 247 pointer lab. The first portion of this lab is following step by step instructions provided by the teacher. This student was talking to a friend who was working on the same project and as a result skipped over a step causing the code to fail to compile.
column4: This occurred at the coding stage and at the skill-based level. I am highly confident this is an Omission Following Interruption as the student picked up the instructions a step ahead after talking to their friend (interruption). I think this could also be Perceptual confusions as their friend was working on the same project and a few steps ahead so it’s possible they were looking at their friend's code and mistook it for theirs causing them to believe they were further along than they were.

column3: Another example is a Student was working on a Python truth table of XOR function in 141. The User inputs two true or false values in the form T or F and a boolean value that is the result of XORing the inputs is returned. The Student used T or F instead of true or false forBoolean values causing a compile error as they were returning a char when the program expected a boolean.
column4: This occurred at the coding stage and the knowledge-based and skill-based levels. This could be a Lack of Knowledge Error as the student hadn’t previously used boolean types so didn’t know to use the keywords “true” and “false”. This could also be Perceptual confusions as the input is a char T or F which has the same function in this project as true or false resulting in the student using the wrong one.

column3: A 145 assignment asked students to create an array of integers with length size. This resulted in approximately 3-4 students students attempting to create new array in the way new instances of an object are created after learning about objects the previous week. They wrote Array a= new Array(int); instead of: int [] a = new int [size];.
column4: This occurred at the coding stage and at the rule-based level. I believe with medium confidence this is a “Strong-but-now-wrong” Rule. Students were familiar with the creation of objects and had successfully used it multiple times in the previous week so when faced with the new rule of creating arrays they mistakenly used the familiar rule of creating objects.

column3: approximately 10-12 students used getters and setters instead of constructors like directed.
column4: This occurred at the design and coding stage as the initial design lacked constructors and they wrote code for just getters and setters instead. I believe with medium confidence this occurs at the rule-based level and is a “Strong-but-now-wrong” Rule. The stronger rule of creating getters and setters to access private variables was used instead of the newer rule of usinging constructors and setting the private variables with input from the constructor arguments.

column3: The second error was using inheritance instead of encapsulation to rewrite the class; around 20-25 students did this (possibly more I should’ve counted exactly but it was a lot).

I am highly confident this is at the knowledge-based level and a Lack of Knowledge of what encapsulation is. It also could be Selectivity and the students focused on the phycologically stagnant object-oriented part instead of the logically important encapsulation part.

column3: Students drawing patterns with turtles in python did not change the color of their drawing at all because this was a sub-goal of the lab requirements and changing the color of the turtle did not at all affect its functionality.

Students using python turtle functionalities are used to utilizing the name of their turtle object in functions, such as MyTurtleName.left(180). However, in the case of Turtle.Tracer() they often wrongly used MyTurtleName.Tracer() since this is an uncommon use case where they are calling the turtle module rather than their personal turtle.

In a program which asks students to represent their knowledge of if statements and boolean logic, there are five possible logical statements that need to be evaluated. One if someone is eligible for representative based on both minimum correct age and years_citizen, one if someone is eligible for senator based on both minimum correct age and years_citizen, one if someone is eligible for representative but not senator, and one if they don’t meet either of these requirements. In many cases, students did not account for the situation in which a person might be eligible for only representative but not server, and thus their program logic defaulted to the “else” statement saying they don’t meet either of the requirements

Students were asked to generate an ASCII triangle which created a new line after each line print so their artwork was continuous. However, the program requirements ask that if the drawing was complete, do not print a final new line. Many students failed this requirement because it was sub-goal that did not affect the functionality, but failed to take it into consideration when creating their program.

When creating turtle drawings, students set their colormode to RGB. The requirements specified the drawing to have some sort of gradient element to it, so often students will have incremental loops to add coloring as the lines are being made. However, many students did not consider cases in which the incremental looping exceeds the color mode (i.e. less than 0 or greater than 255) and thus their program threw an error.
I had to search up turtle documentation when encountering issues such as how to make an ellipsis using the built-in circle function in the turtle module
Students often confused the use of similar-looking functions such as color(), fillcolor(), and/or pencolor() which all are similar but do slightly different things

Students were asked to draw a geometric shape by repeatedly turning the turtle at a certain angle and moving forward in multiple nested loops. Many students correctly set up the loop but forgot to include the final turtle.hideturtle() command required by the rubric. The omission did not affect the drawing’s correctness but failed the requirement checklist, since hiding the turtle was merely a sub-goal of the requirements but does not affect the functionality of the turtle program.

Students called turtle.update() inside a loop, causing their program to lag or draw slowly because the screen was being redrawn after every line segment instead of once at the end. This happened because they were following a familiar pattern of updating after each change (as done in other projects), not realizing that in this context, it should only be done once. Additionally, this meant that they no longer were fulfilling the program requirements stating that their program should run and finish within only a few seconds

Students (and myself) accidentally typed fw() instead of forward() or fd() when instructing the turtle to move. Since fw() is not a defined function in the turtle module, this caused a NameError. This slip typically occurred when students were typing quickly, thinking “forward,” and abbreviated it inconsistently, showing a mismatch between their intention and their motor execution.

column3: When programming physics logic in Unity I called physics changes in Update() instead of FixedUpdate().
column4: Update() updates based on your framerate while FixedUpdate() updates based on time, and tying game physics to framerate is not a good idea. I was unaware that Update() was frame based and just assumed it was time based.

column3: I used the wrong variable name in a function. The function was created to select an item after the cursor was hovering over it for a set time. column3: I added the wrong prefab object to a Unity scene. A prefab is a blueprint object that can be created then easily duplicated. I added a FacultyObject instead of an EventObject to the scene. The two objects look the same until they have their UI updated during runtime from a webscraper.
column4: This was another Perceptual confusions because I mistook one object for the other.

column3: I used the Console.WriteLine function in a Unity C# script, which is the usual function used to print to console, however in this specific situation I was needing my output to be printed to the debug console, which Console.WriteLine does not print to, I instead needed to use Debug.Log.
column4: This was a case of “Strong-but-now-wrong ” because Console.WriteLine is used in most C# programs but was the incorrect choice for this specific situation.

column3: While working on a Unity project I deleted a script that was causing issues during debugging another script. column3: No validation of  vector embeddings  - if sentence_model  fails or returns  incorrect  dimensions,  database query will  fail silently
column4: Developer  implemented happypath where  model.encode()  always succeeds.  Exception handling  returns generic error  without checking if  embedding  dimensions match  database vector  dimensions. Lack of  input validation on  ML model output.

column3: SQL injection  vulnerability if  treatment names or  filter values contain  SQL  metacharacters and  parameterization  fails
column4: While parameterized  queries are used, the  filter parsing logic  (`filter_str.split(':',  1)`) doesn't check  over values before  they're incorporated  into search  embeddings.

column3: Memory leak  potential - search_cache and  filter_cache can  grow unbounded  with unique query combinations exceeding LRU max size
column4: Despite a max_size,  LRU eviction is  simplistic and with  enough unique query  combinations  memory could grow faster than expected. Growth rate underestimated

column3: No database  connection pooling,  each API request  creates new  connection, causing  performance  degradation under  load
column4: used  `psycopg2.connect()`  without connection  pooling. Under high  concurrent load,  connection creation  overhead may  overwhelm. Good for  small projects, not for  this.

column3: Bias assessment  fields displayed in  frontend might be  empty for most  studies

column3: SQL query crashed  when user_email  field contained  NULL values,  causing bulk upload  API to fail for  records with  missing email  addresses
column4: While writing a WHERE  clause filter, I assumed all  email fields would have  values and didn't include  NULL handling (IS NULL  check). When processing  legacy data with missing  emails, the query returned  unexpected results.

column3: VBA script left  database  connections open  after bulk import,  eventually  exhausting  connection pool and  preventing other  users from  accessing database
column4: After getting interrupted  by a team meeting while  writing the connection  cleanup code, I resumed  work but jumped ahead to  testing the main  functionality, skipping the  connection.Close()  statement in the error  handling block.

column3: JavaScript  validation logic  used assignment  operator (=) instead  of equality operator (==), causing form  validation to always  pass even with  invalid data
column4: While writing an if  statement to check status  field, I typed "if (status =  'active')" instead of "if  (status == 'active')". This looked correct initially  since both operators use  the equals symbol.

column3: VBA loop  processing records  used "For i = 1 To  recordCount" but  array was 0 - indexed, causing  last record to be  skipped and  throwing "Index out  of bounds" error
column4: Coming from SQL where  row numbering starts at 1,  I applied the same logic to  VBA arrays without  considering that VBA can  use 0 -based indexing. I  automatically applied the  familiar 1 -based  approach from SQL.

column3: Used INNER JOIN  instead of LEFT  JOIN in SQL query,  causing bulk upload  validation to  exclude valid  records that didn't  have matching  entries in reference  table
column4: When querying to validate  uploaded data against a  reference table, I used  INNER JOIN (the join  type I use most frequently)  without considering that  some valid records might  not have matches in the  reference table

column3: Bulk upload API  completed  successfully but  didn't log which  records failed  validation, making  it impossible to  debug why certain  rows were rejected
column4: After successfully  implementing the main  upload functionality and  seeing it work, I  considered the task  complete and moved on to  testing. Error logging was  a final cleanup step that wasn't strictly necessary  for the feature to "work."

column3: SQL query used  hard-coded table  name  "test_uploads"  instead of  production table  "prod_uploads",  causing bulk upload  to write to wrong  database table in  production
column4: During development, I  tested with "test_uploads"  table. When moving to  production, I continued  using the same query  structure I'd been using  for weeks, forgetting to  parameterize or update  the table name.

column3: JavaScript  validation  compared user  input "Active"  against database  value "active" using  === operator,  failing validation  for records with  different  capitalization
column4: When implementing status  validation, I didn't notice  that the database stores  status in lowercase while  the UI displays it  capitalized. The case  difference wasn't visually  obvious when I tested with  matching cases.

column3: Bulk upload API  accepted  unsanitized user  input directly into  SQL query, creating  SQL injection  vulnerability when  special characters  were uploaded
column4: Focused on getting the  upload functionality  working, I didn't realize  that user input needed to  be sanitized before being  used in SQL queries. Lack  of security training meant  I wasn't aware this was a  required consideration.

column3: Bulk upload API  timed out when  processing files  larger than 1000  rows because batch  processing wasn't  implemented; all  tested uploads  during development  were under 100  rows

column3: While reading in a digital signature package in Java, I used sb.append(line).append (System.lineSeparator()) after each line was read. A.feat: return f”tend to retrieve {A}” else: return f”not strong-but-now-wrong” strong-but-now-wrong(“font size requires an int”) -> “tend to retrieve variable requires a list” Because I had been working with variables that require lists very frequently, I mistakenly applied this strong rule of the variables of this function needing a list onto the font variable, which was an error since the font variable used a different rule.

"char* buffer[size]" was used 
instead of "char buffer[size]".
column4:
The name of a variable is usually preceded 
by all information about its type, but arrays 
are an exception to this

column3: The array was not nullterminated.
column4:
I didn’t know how arrays worked in C, and 
thought the specification for the array to be 
null-terminated was superfluous.

column3:

column3: The array was not populated.

and forgot to resume the main task after 
completing subtasks.

column3:

update the priority.
column4:
A constraint on the inputs was removed, and 
it seemed like the queue manager didn’t need 
to be refactored to account for them.

implemented.

column3:

signaled the wrong object 
when they were finished 
running.
column4:
I created a static field in a class and later 
refactored the class to use a different 
workflow that required the corresponding 
field not to be static.

column3:

couldn’t read anything from object B to set its 
state from, but object C still needed to be 
signaled to read object A’s state
